# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-amplify
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-amplify/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] In software development, **front end** refers to the presentation layer that users interact with, while **back end** refers to the data management and processing behind the scenes.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] In the client–server model, the client is usually considered the front end, handling most user-facing tasks, and the server is the back end, mainly managing data and logic.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] In software architecture, there can be many layers between the hardware and end user.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] The *front end* is an abstraction, simplifying the underlying components by providing a user-friendly interface, while the *back end* handles data storage and business logic.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] In telecommunication, the front end can be considered a device or service, while the back end is the infrastructure that supports the provision of services.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] A rule of thumb is that the front end, or client side, includes any components manipulated by the user.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] The back end, or server side, usually resides on the server, often far removed physically from the user.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] There are many different ways the terms 'front end' and 'back end' can be defined in the context of software.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] For example, in content management systems, the front end refers to views facing end users, and the back end refers to views facing administrative users.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] Similarly, within the field of speech synthesis, the front end refers to the part of the synthesis system that converts the input text into a symbolic phonetic representation, and the back end converts the symbolic phonetic representation into actual sounds.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] In programming language compilers, the front end translates computer source code into an intermediate representation, and the back end produces executable code from the intermediate representation.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] The back end usually optimizes to produce code that runs faster.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] The front end/back end distinction can also separate a parser that deals with source code from a compiler that generates and optimizes executable code.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] Some designs, such as GCC, offer multiple front end options (parsing different source languages) and multiple back end options (generating code for different target processors).
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] Some graphical user interface (GUI) applications act as a thin front end for underlying command-line interface (CLI) programs, to save users from having to learn the CLI terminology and commands.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] Another way to understand the differences between the front end and back end is to consider the knowledge that each requires of a software developer.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] The example lists below focus on web development.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] The front end communicates with the back end through an API.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] In the case of web and mobile front ends, the API is often based on HTTP requests/responses.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] An API can also reduce the front-end processing load by using different back-end services for different front-end interfaces, such as in the "Back end For Front end" (BFF) pattern.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] In computer networking, *front end* can refer to hardware that connects devices to the network, provides security such as a DMZ, or converts data into a transportable format.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] *Back end* refers to hardware that handles and transports data within the network.
[src:aws-amplify/front-and-back-ends] In processor design, *front-end design* can refer to the initial description of a circuit's behavior in a hardware description language such as Verilog, while *back-end design* can refer to the process of mapping that behavior to physical transistors on a die.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:aws-amplify/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Web and mobile apps require a similar set of features on the backend, including notification service, integration with social networks, and cloud storage.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Each of these services has its own API that must be individually incorporated into an app, a process that can be time-consuming and complicated for app developers.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers form a bridge between the frontend of an application and various cloud-based backends via a unified API and SDK.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Providing a consistent way to manage backend data means that developers do not need to redevelop their own backend for each of the services that their apps need to access, potentially saving both time and money.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers offer different set of features and backend tools.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers also come in different types, suiting developers of different needs.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Most BaaS providers host backend platforms on their cloud servers.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] They also manage the infrastructure, security, and scalability of the platforms.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Developers can access the backend services via a web interface or the provided APIs.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Some examples of cloud-based BaaS include Firebase (hosted on Google Cloud Platform), AWS Amplify (hosted on Amazon Web Services), and Microsoft Azure Mobile Apps (hosted on Microsoft Azure).
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Self-hosted BaaS allow developers to host backend on their own servers, providing more flexibility and potential to customization compared to cloud-based BaaS, which often is more difficult to migrate from.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] However, developers are also in charge of managing the infrastructure, security, and scalability of their servers.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Mobile backend as a service (MBaaS) is a type of BaaS specifically for applications deployed in mobile systems.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] While some references use MBaaS interchangeably for BaaS, BaaS can have a wider variety of support such as for web apps and desktop apps.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers generate revenue from their services in various ways, often using a freemium model.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Under this model, a client receives a certain number of free active users or API calls per month, and pays a fee for each user or call over this limit.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Alternatively, clients can pay a set fee for a package which allows for a greater number of calls or active users per month.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] There are also flat fee plans that make the pricing more predictable.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Some of the providers offer the unlimited API calls inside their free plan offerings.
[src:aws-amplify/mobile-backend-as-a-service] Another business model that has been used by a lot of BaaS providers is PAYG (pay as you go), which has a flexible cost based on developers' usage of database, storage, bandwidth, function calls, user numbers etc.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] A **progressive web application** (**PWA**), or **progressive web app**, is a type of web app that can be installed on a device as a standalone application.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] PWAs are installed using the offline cache of the device's web browser.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] PWAs were introduced from 2016 as an alternative to native (device-specific) applications, with the advantage that they do not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] They can be used on a range of different systems, including desktop and mobile devices.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Publishing the app to digital distribution systems, such as the Apple App Store, Google Play, or the Microsoft Store on Windows, is optional.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Because a PWA is delivered in the form of a webpage or website built using common web technologies including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and WebAssembly, it can work on any platform with a PWA-compatible browser.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] As of 2025, PWA features are supported to varying degrees by Google Chrome, Apple Safari, Brave, Firefox for Android, Microsoft Edge, and Firefox for Windows.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] At Apple's Worldwide Developers Conference in 2007, Steve Jobs announced that the iPhone would "run applications created with Web 2.0 Internet standards".
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] No software development kit (SDK) was required, and the apps would be fully integrated into the device through the Safari browser engine.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] This model was later switched to the App Store, as a means of appeasing frustrated developers.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] In October 2007 Jobs announced that an SDK would be launched the following year.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] As a result, although Apple continued to support web apps, the vast majority of iOS applications shifted toward the App Store.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Beginning in the early 2010s dynamic web pages allowed web technologies to be used to create interactive web applications.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Responsive web design, and the screen-size flexibility it provides have made PWA development more accessible.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Continued enhancements to HTML, CSS, and JavaScript allowed web applications to incorporate greater levels of interactivity, making native-like experiences possible on a website.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] It was intended to be an open-source operating system for running web apps as native apps on mobile devices.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Firefox OS was based on the Gecko rendering engine with a user interface called Gaia, written in HTML5.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] The development of Firefox OS ended in 2016, and the project was completely discontinued in 2017, although a fork of Firefox OS was used as the basis of KaiOS, a feature phone platform.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Google then put significant efforts into promoting PWA development for Android.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Firefox introduced support for service workers in 2016, and Microsoft Edge and Apple Safari followed in 2018, making service workers available on all major systems.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] By 2019, PWAs were supported by desktop versions of some browsers, including Microsoft Edge (on Windows) and Google Chrome (on Windows, macOS, ChromeOS, and Linux).
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] In December 2020, Firefox for desktop abandoned the implementation of PWAs (specifically, removed the prototype "site-specific browser" configuration that had been available as an experimental feature).
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] A Firefox architect noted: "The signal I hope we are sending is that PWA support is not coming to desktop Firefox anytime soon." Mozilla supports PWAs on Android and plans to keep supporting it.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Firefox version 143.0, released in September 2025, added support for PWA on Windows.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps are all designed to work on any browser that is compliant with the appropriate web standards.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] As with other cross-platform solutions, the goal is to help developers build cross-platform apps more easily than they would with native apps.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps employ the progressive enhancement web development strategy.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Some progressive web apps use an architectural approach called the App Shell Model.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] In this model, service workers store the Basic User Interface or "shell" of the responsive web design web application in the browser's offline cache.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] This model allows for PWAs to maintain native-like use with or without web connectivity.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] This can improve loading time, by providing an *initial static frame*, a layout or architecture into which content can be loaded progressively as well as dynamically.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] There are many technologies commonly used to create progressive web apps.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] A web application is considered a PWA if it satisfies the installation criteria, thus can work offline and can be added to the device's home screen.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] To meet this definition, all PWAs require at minimum a manifest and a service worker.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Other technologies may be used to store data, communicate with servers or execute code.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] This metadata is crucial for an app to be added to a home screen or otherwise listed alongside native apps.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] iOS Safari partially implements manifests, while most of the PWA metadata can be defined via Apple-specific extensions to the meta tags.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] These tags allow developers to enable full-screen display, define icons and splash screens, and specify a name for the application.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] A service worker is a web worker that implements a programmable network proxy that can respond to web/HTTP requests from the main document.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] It is able to check the availability of a remote server, cache content when that server is available, and serve that content to the document later.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Service workers, like any other web workers, work separately from the main document context.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Service workers can handle push notifications and synchronize data in the background, cache or retrieve resource requests, intercept network requests and receive centralized updates independently of the document that registered them, even when that document is not loaded.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Service workers go through a three-step lifecycle of Registration, Installation and Activation.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Registration involves telling the browser the location of the service worker in preparation for installation.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Installation occurs when there is no service worker installed in the browser for the web app, or if there is an update to the service worker.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Activation occurs when all of the PWA's pages are closed, so that there is no conflict between the previous version and the updated one.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] The lifecycle also helps maintain consistency when switching among versions of a service worker since only a single service worker can be active for a domain.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] WebAssembly allows precompiled code to run in a web browser, at near-native speed.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Thus, libraries written in languages such as C can be added to web apps.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Announced in 2015 and first released in March 2017, WebAssembly became a W3C recommendation on December 5, 2019 and it received the Programming Languages Software Award from ACM SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] is a WHATWG standard API that enables key–value storage in modern browsers.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] (that enables storage that persists across sessions).
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] is a W3C standard database API available in all major browsers.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] objects and any structures representable as a string.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] providing additional constructs around it.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] In 2017, Twitter released Twitter Lite, a PWA alternative to the official native Android and iOS apps.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] According to Twitter, Twitter Lite consumed only 1–3% of the size of the native apps.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Starbucks provides a PWA that is 99.84% smaller than its equivalent iOS app.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] After deploying its PWA, Starbucks doubled the number of online orders, with desktop users ordering at about the same rate as mobile app users.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] A 2018 review published by Forbes, found that users of Pinterest's PWA spent 40% more time on the site compared to the previous mobile website.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Ad revenue rates also increased by 44%, and core engagements by 60%.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Flipkart saw 60% of customers who had uninstalled their native app return to use the Flipkart PWA.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Lancôme saw an 84% decrease in time until the page is interactive, leading to a 17% increase in conversions and a 53% increase in mobile sessions on iOS with their PWA.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Since a PWA does not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms and is available to users via the web, it is not necessary for developers to release it over digital distribution systems like the Apple App Store, Google Play, Microsoft Store, or Samsung Galaxy Store.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] The major app stores support the publication of PWAs to varying degrees.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Google Play, Microsoft Store, and Samsung Galaxy Store support PWAs, but Apple App Store does not.
[src:aws-amplify/progressive-web-app] Microsoft Store publishes some qualifying PWAs automatically (even without app authors' requests) after discovering them via Bing indexing.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:aws-amplify/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
